QoEnet is easier to run on a chip because the model is just a series of simple decisions. Each prediction is basically a few `if` comparisons on WiFi features, 
followed by averaging the outputs from several trees. That means the processor only performs very lightweight operations like comparisons and basic arithmetic. 
There are no large matrices, no complex math functions, and no internal state to maintain. Because of this, the code is small, runs very fast, and uses very little memory. 
This makes QoEnet a good fit for embedded firmware in networking devices.

Maestro is harder to run on a chip because it is based on an LSTM neural network. 
Every prediction requires multiple vector multiplications and nonlinear functions such as sigmoid and tanh. 
The model also needs to maintain hidden and cell states across time. These operations require more CPU power, more memory, and more complex code. 
It can still run on a chip, but it typically needs a stronger processor and more optimization.

In practice, QoEnet can run comfortably on many embedded processors used in networking equipment. 
Examples include ARM Cortex-M microcontrollers such as STM32F7 or STM32H7, ESP32 chips, or embedded CPUs inside WiFi access point SoCs from vendors like Qualcomm IPQ or Broadcom. 
Maestro can run on larger embedded processors such as ARM Cortex-A based chips, Raspberry Pi class devices, Qualcomm networking SoCs, or MediaTek router processors which is all bigger chips and his 
arger footpring on the cirucit in general. These platforms provide the extra compute and memory needed for neural network inference. 

In short, QoEnet fits naturally into small embedded systems, while Maestro usually requires a stronger embedded CPU to run efficiently.
